Sep 18 2009 	Faded 'old money' at the top of the city	There were a few surprises around this one! Perhaps the biggest being that if we had paid the $375 rack rate demanded when we called to book, we'd have been somewhat underwhelmed. However, at the $165/night obtained via an internet booking site courtesy of Trip Advisor we felt more than comfortable with this slightly faded venerable old place at the top of Nob Hill by the cathedral. The entrance and entertainment areas are nice. However, once you get onto the accommodation floors, carpets are off-colour and rooms far from luxurious whilst more than adequate. Bathrooms are big with grand old marble sinks (his &amp; hers!). We were shocked to find that our room was clearly designed as part of a suite and the gap under the joining door was big enough (over 1&quot;) to hear all speech, and more. God knows what the neighbours thought of us! There's a useful small 'business centre' with computers and printers. The bar on the ground floor is all dark panelled wood with a lighted fire even in September and a tinkling pianist who although human seems to repeat himself like a loop tape. Adjoining, the restaurant is just as dark which is a bit off-putting at breakfast, but our queries as to whether there was a little daylight to help our psyches wake up were met with &quot;Goodness me SIr, no. This is a VERY historic restaurant!&quot;. Actually the waiting staff couldn't have been more efficient or charming, and the cooking was great.The facilities of the spa (pool, sauna, steam room, exercise room etc)) are available inclusive to hotel guests and its a great perk. Very nice indeed, if somewhat compact.Overall, for lovers of the older style of hotel, this place will certainly please, but dont pay the full rate. And remember that, if on foot, you certainly wont need the spa's exercise room after the stiff climb up Nob Hill!	
